<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16079</anchor> <rss>jms-00C9.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C9</addr>  <route>jms-00C9.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Successor algebra</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>. A <em>successor algebra</em> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> is defined to be a <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">algebra</link> <tex>X</tex> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> together with a morphism <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ s _{ X } }}{ X }</tex> in <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> called the <em>successor map</em>.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16080</anchor> <rss>jms-00CM.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00CM</addr>  <route>jms-00CM.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors> <contributor><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></contributor></authors> <title>Successor algebras</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>16081</anchor> <rss>jms-00C9.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C9</addr>  <route>jms-00C9.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Successor algebra</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>. A <em>successor algebra</em> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> is defined to be a <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">algebra</link> <tex>X</tex> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> together with a morphism <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ s _{ X } }}{ X }</tex> in <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> called the <em>successor map</em>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>16082</anchor> <rss>jms-00CA.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00CA</addr>  <route>jms-00CA.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Homomorphism of successor algebras</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A homomorphism of <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebras</link> is a <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">monad algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ h }}{ Y }</tex> that preserves the successor operation:</p>      <center><img src="resources/4dbc8d680267c0533116f6a74f842407-web.svg"/></center>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>3</crumb></trail> <anchor>16083</anchor> <rss>jms-00CC.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00CC</addr>  <route>jms-00CC.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The successor restriction of a successor algebra</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be an <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>. We define the <em>successor restriction</em> of <tex>X</tex> to be the <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> <tex>s \cdot X  : \equiv   s _{ X } \cdot  X</tex> defined by <link href="jms-00CQ.xml" type="local" title="Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms">restricting</link> <tex>X</tex> along its successor map.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>4</crumb></trail> <anchor>16084</anchor> <rss>jms-00CN.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CN</addr>  <route>jms-00CN.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> on a fixed point</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter> 
<p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T} \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>. The <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced by</link> <tex>X</tex> can be equipped with the structure of a <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> by defining <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ s _{ \bar { X } } }}{ X }</tex> to be the following map:</p>      <center><img src="resources/cf67a8c6a923ff6f7dd3883a087e70b0-web.svg"/></center>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>5</crumb></trail> <anchor>16085</anchor> <rss>jms-00CR.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CR</addr>  <route>jms-00CR.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link> to the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}   \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link>. Then a homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ s \cdot X }</tex> also tracks a <link href="jms-00CA.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of successor algebras">successor algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>, where <tex>\bar { I }</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>s \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">successor restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline>   We have <link href="jms-00CK.xml" type="local" title="Lifting homomorphisms to the induced monad algebra">already seen</link> that <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ s \cdot X }</tex> tracks an <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>. It remains to show that this homomorphism preserves the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">successor operation</link>.
  <ol>    <li>      We first unfold the successor operation of the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> on <tex>I</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/d5edc41ec718645e12b1826e39fe92ec-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Then we use the algebra property of <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ s \cdot X }</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/59f3aa943874cb25d36d02053a50e7c9-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Then we unfold the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">restricted algebra structure</link>.
            <center><img src="resources/46e6731c1bd42216bc96a1d3231be24c-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Finally we the unitality of the <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link> <tex>X</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/b0cd0b78bfb23cf347f6cd7bef104cdc-web.svg"/></center>      </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16086</anchor> <rss>jms-00C5.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C5</addr>  <route>jms-00C5.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebra for a monad</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}   \equiv   { \left ( T, \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>. An <em>algebra</em> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> is defined to be a <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor"><tex>T</tex>-algebra</link> <tex>X</tex> satisfying the following unit and associativity laws:</p>      <center><img src="resources/c79ae53e7fbd77676b8225472443fb49-web.svg"/></center>        <center><img src="resources/d19bee81b9d4cd708dace75e204f062f-web.svg"/></center>  </mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16087</anchor> <rss>jms-00CR.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CR</addr>  <route>jms-00CR.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link> to the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}   \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link>. Then a homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ s \cdot X }</tex> also tracks a <link href="jms-00CA.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of successor algebras">successor algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>, where <tex>\bar { I }</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>s \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">successor restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline>   We have <link href="jms-00CK.xml" type="local" title="Lifting homomorphisms to the induced monad algebra">already seen</link> that <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ s \cdot X }</tex> tracks an <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>. It remains to show that this homomorphism preserves the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">successor operation</link>.
  <ol>    <li>      We first unfold the successor operation of the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> on <tex>I</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/d5edc41ec718645e12b1826e39fe92ec-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Then we use the algebra property of <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ s \cdot X }</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/59f3aa943874cb25d36d02053a50e7c9-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Then we unfold the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">restricted algebra structure</link>.
            <center><img src="resources/46e6731c1bd42216bc96a1d3231be24c-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Finally we the unitality of the <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link> <tex>X</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/b0cd0b78bfb23cf347f6cd7bef104cdc-web.svg"/></center>      </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16088</anchor> <rss>jms-00CN.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CN</addr>  <route>jms-00CN.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> on a fixed point</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter> 
<p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T} \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>. The <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced by</link> <tex>X</tex> can be equipped with the structure of a <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> by defining <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ s _{ \bar { X } } }}{ X }</tex> to be the following map:</p>      <center><img src="resources/cf67a8c6a923ff6f7dd3883a087e70b0-web.svg"/></center>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16089</anchor> <rss>jms-00CA.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00CA</addr>  <route>jms-00CA.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Homomorphism of successor algebras</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A homomorphism of <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebras</link> is a <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">monad algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ h }}{ Y }</tex> that preserves the successor operation:</p>      <center><img src="resources/4dbc8d680267c0533116f6a74f842407-web.svg"/></center>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16090</anchor> <rss>jms-00CC.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00CC</addr>  <route>jms-00CC.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The successor restriction of a successor algebra</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be an <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>. We define the <em>successor restriction</em> of <tex>X</tex> to be the <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> <tex>s \cdot X  : \equiv   s _{ X } \cdot  X</tex> defined by <link href="jms-00CQ.xml" type="local" title="Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms">restricting</link> <tex>X</tex> along its successor map.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16091</anchor> <rss>joyal-moerdijk-1995.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>joyal-moerdijk-1995</addr>  <route>joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml</route> <date><year>1995</year>  </date> <authors><author><link href="andréjoyal.xml" type="local">André Joyal</link></author><author><link href="iekemoerdijk.xml" type="local">Ieke Moerdijk</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebraic set theory</title> <meta name="venue">Cambridge University Press</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> </tree></references></backmatter></tree>